# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2009-german-federal-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Federal elections were held in all the 38 states of the German Confederation on 1 May 1848 to elect members of a new National Assembly known as the Frankfurt Parliament.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The ballot was not secret, and elected 585 members, mostly from the middle class.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament (*Vorparlement*) convened in the Paulskirche in Frankfurt on 31 March 1848 and ended on 30 May 1849.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Most of the 521 members of it were from South and West Germany, including 2 from Austria.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] There were 141 representatives from Prussia, of which 100 were from the Rhineland with a strong liberal tradition.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament dispersed on 3 April having appointed a committee of 50.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The radicals Friedrich Hecker and Gustav Struve were excluded as they had walked out; they had favored the abolition of both hereditary monarchy and standing armies, and a Federal constitution on North American lines.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The rebuffed Hecker proclaimed the German Republic in Baden on 12 April, but the so-called *Heckenputsch* failed within a week.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Hecker escaped to Switzerland and became a farmer in the United States.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Later Struve also went into exile (in Switzerland and the United States) before returning to Germany.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament had favoured universal suffrage, although individual states set their own qualifications.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] While Austria, Prussia and Schleswig-Holstein imposed no restrictions, farm hands were excluded in Baden and Saxony.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Bavaria and Wutternberg excluded domestic servants and workers, and Bavaria included only those paying direct taxation.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament set the ratio of one deputy to the National Assembly per 50,000 inhabitants of the German Confederation, totaling 649 deputies.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] However, Czech-majority constituencies in Bohemia and Moravia boycotted the election, reducing the total to 585.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Those elected included 157 judges and lawyers, 138 high officials, over a hundred university and high school teachers, and about 40 merchants and industrialists.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Most of the 90 members of the nobility were in the learned professions, and there was only one peasant and four *handwerkers* (skilled artisans or craftsmen).
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Frankfurt Parliament convened on 18 May at Frankfurt, when the members walked in solemn procession to the Paulskirche accompanied by the roar of cannon and the ringing of bells.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] Elections to the Zollparlament of the German Zollverein were held in February and March 1868.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] The Zollparlament consisted of the members of the Reichstag of the North German Confederation and members from the South German states.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] Those South German members were elected in these elections, the North Germans were the Reichstag members elected the previous year.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] In total, 85 South Germans were elected: 48 from Bavaria, 14 from Baden, six from Hesse-Darmstadt (additionally to the three Reichstag members in the province of Upper Hesse), and 17 from Württemberg.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] Most of the South German Zollparlament members were anti-Prussian regionalists.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] The outcome of the elections did not encourage Bismarck to take advantage of the Zollparlament as a vehicle for the politician unification of Germany.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] A federal election for the first Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 3 March 1871, 45 days after the founding of the Empire.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The voting took place under the provisions of the short-lived Constitution of the German Confederation.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] With certain limitations, all German males over 25 years of age were eligible to vote.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The National Liberal Party, one of the key supporters of the German unification of 1871, emerged as the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The newly founded Catholic Centre Party came in second.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Reichstag approved the new Constitution of the German Empire on 14 April 1871.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It set the legislative period at three years, putting the next election in 1874.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] At the end of the Austro-Prussian War of 1866, the victorious Kingdom of Prussia annexed many of the smaller north German states to form the North German Confederation.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The North German Constitution, which reflected the political ideas of Prussian minister president Otto von Bismarck, included a Reichstag elected according to equal, secret and universal manhood suffrage.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] With minor modifications, the North German Constitution became the Constitution of the German Confederation on 1 January 1871, during the final days of the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Confederation's 297-member Reichstag, last elected in August 1867, was expanded by 85 seats to accommodate the four south German states (Baden, Hesse south of the Main River, Württemberg and Bavaria) that were joining the Confederation to form what would become the German Empire on 18 January.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The election was held under general, equal, direct and secret suffrage.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] All German males over the age of 25 years were able to vote except for active members of the military and recipients of poor relief.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The restrictions on the military were meant to keep it from becoming politicized, while men on relief were considered to be open to political manipulation.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The constitutional guarantee of a secret vote was not safeguarded at the time, since ballot boxes and polling booths were not introduced until 1903.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] If no candidate in a district won an absolute majority of the votes, a runoff election was held between the first- and second-place finishers.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was possible for a replacement candidate to be introduced in a runoff.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was common at the time for individuals to campaign not as a member of a specific party but rather under a more general label such as liberal, conservative, clerical or particularist.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Once the parliament met, such members would join an existing party or work with like-minded representatives to form a new one.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] As a result, the picture of a new Reichstag's party makeup would come into focus only some time after the voting.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Liberalism, supported primarily by the middle class, was the leading political movement at the time of the Empire's foundation.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was divided into two large ideological groups, the liberal left, of which the German Progress Party (DFP) was the largest party, and national liberalism, centered in the National Liberal Party (NLP).
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Both parties had supported Bismarck's unification policies, although the NLP was more consistent in its backing of the Chancellor.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The two main conservative parties were the German Conservative Party and the German Reich Party.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] They backed Bismarck and found their primary support among the nobility and large landowners in the eastern states.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Catholic Centre Party was founded following the election for the Prussian House of Representatives in November 1870.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] On 23 March 1871, a group of Catholic members of the newly elected Reichstag came together to form a Centre Party parliamentary caucus.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The party's membership was almost exclusively Catholic and, unlike most parties of the time, spanned the full range of social classes.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Centre's party program for 1871, entitled "Justice is the basis of governance", promised to protect the federal nature of the Empire and strive for the "constitutional establishment of guarantees of the civic and religious freedom of all citizens".
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Imperial Liberal Party formed after the 1871 election as a liberal-conservative offshoot of the National Liberal Party.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was a party of notables (*Honoratiorenpartei*) that supported Bismarck, rejected parliamentarization and sought to work with both the National Liberals and the Conservative Party.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Workers Party (SDAP) had favored a greater German unification (one which would have included Austria) and during the Franco-Prussian War had advocated "proletarian internationalism".
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] In its founding Eisenach Program of 1869, the party promised to fight for the abolition of class rule, elimination of the capitalist mode of production, a standard working day, and the prohibition of child labor.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Polish Party represented the approximately three million German citizens whose native language was Polish.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Most of them lived in the Prussian provinces of Posen, West Prussia and Silesia.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The parties that supported Bismarck's policies, notably on unification, became the dominant parties in the new Reichstag: the National Liberals, Centre, Conservatives and Progress Party.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Voter turnout was just 51%, the lowest during the life of the Empire.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Historian Volker Ullrich suggests that the lack of voter interest was due to the fact that the initial enthusiasm over the founding of the Empire remained limited primarily to the national-liberal bourgeoisie.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The changes in the results from the previous Reichstag (shown below) are a combination of two previous elections: to the North German Reichstag in 1867 and to the *Zollparlament*, the parliament of the German Customs Union (*Zollverein*), in 1868.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The *Zollparlament* consisted of all members of the North German Reichstag plus 85 representatives elected from the south German states that joined the German Empire in 1871.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] They received as many seats in the new Reichstag as they had held in the *Zollparlament*.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The first meeting of the imperial Reichstag, whose provisional home was the Prussian House of Representatives, took place in the White Hall of the Berlin Palace, the residence of the kings and emperors of Prussia.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Emperor Wilhelm I chose to welcome the Reichstag members there because he did not want to give the impression that he had his subjects to thank for the crown.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The throne of the Holy Roman Emperor Henry III had been brought from Goslar for the occasion, and the victorious Prussian generals, led by Helmuth von Moltke, carried the imperial regalia.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Reichstag approved the new Constitution of the German Empire with just seven 'no' votes on 14 April 1871.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] In one other significant vote, taken on 11 March 1872, the Reichstag replaced church with state supervision of German schools.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The next election was held on 10 January 1874 in accordance with the constitutional three-year term of office for Reichstag members.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] A federal election for the second Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 10 January 1874.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The National Liberal Party remained the largest party in the Reichstag, with 147 of the 397 seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The Centre Party, which had campaigned against the anti-Catholic laws introduced by the government of Chancellor Otto von Bismarck*,* was able to double its vote total from the previous election and placed second.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The Conservative and Imperial Liberal parties lost the most seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The most significant political event to affect the 1874 election was the start in July 1871 of the *Kulturkampf* (Cultural Struggle), an attempt to suppress the political power of Catholicism in Germany.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Chancellor Otto von Bismarck feared that Catholics' loyalty lay more with the Vatican than Germany, and many liberals saw the Catholic Church as politically reactionary.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Although the majority of the anti-Catholic laws affected only Prussia, they were nevertheless a major concern for all German Catholics since Prussia accounted for about two-thirds of the German population.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] One of Bismarck's chief goals in the *Kulturkampf* was to break the Catholic Centre Party.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Catholics made up about one-third of both Prussia's and the Empire's population, and the Centre Party, which had been founded only in December 1870, had placed second in the 1871 election with 58 seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Catholics were most heavily concentrated in the Imperial Territory of Alsace–Lorraine, which had just been won from France in the Franco-Prussian War, in Bavaria, Baden, and the Prussian provinces of Rhineland, Westphalia and heavily Polish Posen.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The major gainers in the 1874 election were the National Liberal Party and the Centre Party; losses affected primarily the Conservative Party and the short-lived Imperial Liberal Party.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Rather than suppressing the Catholic vote, the *Kulturkampf* served to consolidate political Catholicism.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The Centre Party more than doubled the number votes it had received in 1871, from just under 708,000 to over 1.4 million.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] It was the most votes of any party, although the Centre won 56 fewer seats than the National Liberals.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Such a result was possible under the Empire's electoral system if a party was more successful at winning majorities in individual districts and/or won more runoff elections.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] There were 46 runoffs for the 397 seats in 1874.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] 1874 was the first year that representatives from Alsace–Lorraine were elected to the Reichstag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] All 15 opposed the German annexation of the region.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] A federal election for the third Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 10 January 1877.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] It was a regularly scheduled election based on the three-year legislative period established in the imperial constitution.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The voting was strongly influenced by the economic downturn that had followed the Panic of 1873.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The sharp economic downturn that began in late 1873 significantly affected the 1877 Reichstag election.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] Known in Germany as the "founders' crash" (*Gründerkrach*) because it followed the period of rapid growth after the founding of the Empire in 1871, the worldwide Panic of 1873 triggered an economic depression that lasted until 1879 in Germany.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] Particularly hard hit were workers who lost their jobs and members of the middle class who relied on income from stocks.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The economic problems caused Chancellor Otto von Bismarck to shift away from the free trade policies supported by the National Liberals, who were the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] In an early reaction to his policy changes, Rudolph von Delbrück, head of the Reich Chancellery and a strong proponent of free trade, resigned in 1876.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The same year saw the founding of the German Conservative Party, which supported protectionism and endorsed Bismarck's overall policies.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The hardships that the working class faced because of the founders' crash led to a strengthened sense of solidarity among them that was reflected in the SAPD's showing in the 1877 election.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The election overall was favorable to Bismarck.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The German Conservative Party gained 19 seats, the liberal-conservative German Reich Party 6 and the Socialist Workers' Party 3.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] In spite of losing 20 seats, the National Liberals remained the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The other major loser was the liberal German Progress Party, down 14 seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The new Löwe-Berger Group, which had split from them in 1874, won 9 seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] After two assassination attempts against Emperor Wilhelm I in May and June 1878 and disputes over the planned Anti-Socialist Law that Bismarck introduced as a result, the third Reichstag was dissolved by the Emperor at Bismarck's request, and a new election was held on 30 July 1878.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] A federal election for the fourth Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 30 July 1878.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It took place 18 months ahead of schedule after two unsuccessful assassination attempts against Emperor Wilhelm I led Chancellor Otto von Bismarck to request an early dissolution of the Reichstag that had been elected in January 1877.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Bismarck tried to tie the attacks on the Emperor to the Social Democrats and, indirectly, the National Liberals in order to weaken them and strengthen the conservative parties.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Although the National Liberals lost 30 seats and the two main conservative parties gained 38, the National Liberals remained the strongest party in the Reichstag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It went on to pass Bismarck's harsh Anti-Socialist Law in October 1878.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The 1878 election, held just 18 months after the previous Reichstag election, is often referred to as the "assassination-attempt election" (*Attentatswahl*) because it was wholly dominated by the two unsuccessful attempts to assassinate Emperor Wilhelm I in the spring of 1878.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Chancellor Otto von Bismarck took immediate political advantage of the public outrage to attack both the leftist Socialist Workers' Party (the forerunner of the Social Democratic Party, or SPD) and the centrist National Liberals.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] On 20 May Bismarck presented a draft "Law on the Defence Against Social Democratic Outrages" (*Gesetz zur Abwehr sozialdemokratischer Ausschreitungen*), which the Reichstag rejected by a vote of 251 to 57.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The law's wording was so broad that the National Liberals feared that it could be directed against them.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Bismarck had in fact expected that the party, which in 1876 had blocked a bill he had introduced to extend the range of politically criminal acts, would oppose the measure and that he could then brand them as accomplices of the social democrats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The second assassination attempt on 2 June was committed by a man named Karl Nobiling who was suffering under "personal delusions".
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] On the following morning, the Wolff semi-official news agency reported that Nobiling had confessed to having SPD sympathies.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It was all but impossible that he could have done so, however, because he had been badly wounded during the attack and was not capable of responding to questions.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Bismarck nevertheless used the situation to dissolve the Reichstag on 11 June.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Some historians see evidence connecting Bismarck's ministry to Wolff's report and say that it marked the start of the campaign to link Social Democrats to the act and accuse the National Liberals of collusion with them.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] In the campaign for the new Reichstag, the majority of the National Liberals' candidates came from its conservative wing and had already committed themselves to voting for Bismarck's proposed anti-socialist law.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Even some politicians from the left-of-center German Progress Party moved towards the Chancellor.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] One flyer it put out declared that "the social democratic fraud, along with its parasitic plants, is a disgrace to the entire German people".
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The Social Democrats for their part were severely hampered in their ability to campaign.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Although no restrictive laws had yet been passed, prominent social democrats had their houses searched and papers confiscated.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The party was forced to restrict its campaigning to electoral districts in which it already had a dominant position.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] As Bismarck had hoped, conservative parties were the clear winners in the election.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Both the German Reich Party (also known as the Free Conservative Party) and the German Conservative Party picked up 19 seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The National Liberals lost 30 seats but with 97 remained the strongest party in the Reichstag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] In spite of the attacks against it, the Socialist Workers' Party (Social Democrats) lost just four seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Turnout was 63%, only slightly higher than the previous two elections.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] On 19 October 1878, Bismarck's Anti-Socialist Law passed the new Reichstag 221 to 149.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] All National Liberals voted for the law, as did the members of the two conservative parties, while those from the German Progress Party, the Catholic Centre Party – which had been the object of Bismarck's anti-Catholic *Kulturkampf* – and the Socialist Workers' Party voted against it.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The law prohibited societies, meetings, publications, public festivities and processions that "aim[ed] at the overthrow of the existing political or social order through social-democratic, socialist or communist endeavors".
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It also banned collecting or appealing for contributions to support such activities.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Emperor Wilhelm I signed the law on 21 October 1878.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It was subsequently renewed 4 times before it was allowed to expire on 30 September 1890, after Bismarck had resigned as chancellor.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] A federal election for the fifth Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 27 October 1881.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] It was a regularly scheduled election under the Reichstag's three-year terms of office.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The dominant issues were protective tariffs and the government's requests for increased taxes.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The conservative parties, which supported the government, lost seats, leaving the Reichstag without options for a stable majority.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] As a result, Chancellor Otto von Bismarck was unable to realize many of his plans in the new parliament.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Taxes and tariffs were the dominant issue in the 1881 election.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Increasing competition from abroad had led to the passage of protective tariffs on agricultural and industrial goods in 1879.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The Catholic Centre Party, German Conservative Party and 27 out of 97 members of the National Liberal Party voted for the tariff bill, while the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the remainder of the National Liberals opposed it.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The differences of opinion within the National Liberal Party led to a group of members from its left wing splitting off and forming the Liberal Union in 1880.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] In spite of the income from tariffs, the government needed additional revenue to cover its expenses.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] In the autumn of 1880, the Reichstag approved a seven-year budget for the military, but a majority resisted the additional tax increases that the government later requested.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Chancellor Otto von Bismarck hoped that the election of 1881 would improve the chances of passing his tax package.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The parties that Bismarck generally relied on for votes lost seats in the election.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The Centre, Conservatives and German Reich Party (Free Conservatives) together had 177 seats, down 33 from the previous election and well short of the 199 needed for a majority.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Opposite the conservative grouping stood the Liberal Union and German Progress Party with 106 seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] They and the National Liberal Party with its 45 seats formed a *Kartell* with the aim of coming to a mutual understanding before critical votes.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The share of the vote going to the Social Democratic Party (officially still named the Socialist Workers' Party) dropped by just 1.5% despite the harsh restrictions placed on it by the Anti-Socialist Law in 1878.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The number of seats it won in the Reichstag actually rose, from 9 to 13.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Because he lacked a majority in the Reichstag, Bismarck's only choices were to try to put together temporary blocs that would support him or to rule without parliament.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] His attempts to do the latter ran into opposition from both his advisors and the Reichstag, which refused to grant him the necessary funds.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] As a result, many of Bismarck's post-election reform plans had to be shelved.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Emperor Wilhelm I was so unhappy about how little the SPD's share of the vote had decreased that he sent a note to the Reichstag saying that the government would hold to its tax and tariff policies even against the Reichstag's opposition.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] He also issued a decree to public officials requiring them to advocate the government's positions.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Bismarck came to realize that he needed to change course and try to win over the socialists.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] In November 1881, he announced a bill to provide workers with insurance against accident, illness, disability and old age.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The corresponding laws began to go into effect in 1883.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The Anti-Socialist Law remained in effect until 1890.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 2009 to elect the members of the 17th Bundestag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) won the election, and the three parties formed a new centre-right government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] While CDU/CSU's share of votes decreased slightly, it was more than compensated by the gains of their "desired coalition partner", the liberal FDP, that won the strongest result in its history.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] CDU and CSU's former partner in the "Grand coalition", the Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Frank-Walter Steinmeier, conceded defeat after dropping by more than 11 percentage points, receiving its hitherto worst result since the end of the Second World War (only undercut in 2017 and 2025).
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] At 70.8 percent, the voter turnout was the lowest in a German federal election since 1949.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Since the 2005 election, Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) had governed in a grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] However, it was her stated goal to win a majority for CDU/CSU and FDP (the CDU/CSU's traditional coalition partner) in 2009.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Foreign minister and Vice-Chancellor Frank-Walter Steinmeier (SPD) was formally nominated as his party's chancellor-candidate at a convention on 18 October 2008.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] He aimed to form a government in which the SPD was the strongest party, but which also excluded the left-socialist party The Left.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The election campaign was considered exceptionally boring, which may be attributable to a perceived lack of charisma on the part of the leaders of the CDU and SPD.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Another reason pointed to for the sedate campaign is that the CDU and SPD both defended the record of their grand coalition, and facing the possibility of having to continue the grand coalition in a friendly manner.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Merkel was content with the low-key campaign style, which was largely seen as benefiting her party because of her high approval ratings.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] CDU candidate Vera Lengsfeld released a campaign poster featuring herself and Merkel in a way that emphasised their cleavage.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The poster bore the slogan "We have more to offer" (German: "*Wir haben mehr zu bieten*").
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] On 23 September 2009, four days before the federal elections, German police raided the Berlin headquarters of the National Democratic Party of Germany NPD to investigate claims that letters sent from the NPD to politicians from immigrant backgrounds incited racial hatred.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The federal election was the final and most important election in what is called a *Superwahljahr* (super election year) in Germany.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and FDP, with an average vote share of around 50% in pre-election polling during the weeks before the election, were clearly ahead of the other traditional coalition partners in Germany, SPD and the Greens.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU received a slightly lower proportion than in the previous election, with the Bavarian CSU receiving its lowest vote share in decades.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Overall, the CDU/CSU had their worst vote share in 60 years.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] In contrast, their preferred coalition partner, the liberal FDP, gained nearly 5% points to give it 14.6% of the vote, the best result of its history.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The big loser of the election was the SPD, which received its worst result ever in a federal election, receiving only 23% of the total party vote and suffering the biggest percentage loss of any party in German federal election history in 60 years.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] The two other parties represented in the Bundestag, the Left and the Greens, both made large gains and received the highest vote share of their respective histories.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] For the first time, The Left won constituency seats outside its traditional stronghold of East Berlin.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] As a result of the losses by the SPD and the gains by the FDP, the alliance of the CDU/CSU and FDP received an outright majority of seats, ensuring that Angela Merkel would continue as chancellor.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] Had the CDU/CSU and FDP failed to win a majority of seats, possible alternative coalitions may have included a continuation of the grand coalition of CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:2009-german-federal-election/2009-german-federal-election] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was specifically ruled out by FDP leader Guido Westerwelle.
